    "### **Project Introduction:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Depression is a widespread mental health condition that goes beyond temporary sadness, affecting thoughts, emotions, behavior and physical well-being. It arises from a complex interplay of biological, psychological and social factors, with prolonged stress and lack of support increasing vulnerability. Globally, about 3.8% of the population, roughly 280 million people, experience depression, while rates in Singapore are notably higher at 6 to 7%. Young adults aged 15 to 29 and women are among the most affected groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "Depression is deeply concerning because of its wide-ranging impact on individuals and society. It is the leading cause of disability worldwide, diminishing quality of life and functioning across personal, academic and social domains. Depression significantly increases the risk of suicide, particularly among young people, and is closely linked to physical health problems such as cardiovascular disease and other chronic conditions. On a broader scale, it imposes a heavy economic burden through reduced productivity and rising healthcare costs. These factors highlight why addressing depression is not only a matter of personal well-being but also a critical public health and societal priority.\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Moving Into Singapore Context:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Building on the broader societal impact of depression, our focus narrows to individuals at the National University of Singapore (NUS), particularly young people in their late teens to early adulthood. This demographic is especially vulnerable as young adults face unique pressures from academic demands, social transitions and the challenges of early independence. With depression rates in Singapore already higher than the global average, the need to address mental health among university students becomes even more pressing.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite the availability of counseling services, University Healthcare Centre (UHC) counselors encounter difficulties in providing continuous and timely support. Unavoidable gaps between counseling sessions can leave students without adequate monitoring, leading to delayed detection of worsening symptoms. These lapses increase the risk of relapse or more severe depressive episodes, underscoring the urgency of finding innovative solutions to bridge these support gaps and ensure sustained care for vulnerable students.\n",
    "\n",
    "------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Our Problem Statement:**\n",
    "\n",
    "**\"University Health Centre (UHC) counsellors face challenges in providing continous and timely support to NUS students experiencing depression, due to intervals between counselling sessions. These gaps in monitoring and intervention may contribute to delayed detection of symptom deterioration, increasing the risk of relapse or worsening depressive episodes.\"**\n",
    "\n",
    "### **3 Jobs To Be Done:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Detect Deterioration Early**: When a student's depressive symptoms worsen between sessions, I want to detect early warning signs so that intervention can occur without his/her condition worsening further.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Prioritize High Risk Students**: When counsellors manage multiple cases, I want to efficiently identify which students require urgent attention so that limited session capacity can be delegated effectively, without providing insufficient support for at-risk students.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Monitor Trends At Population Level**: When UHC evaluates service demand, I want to identify trends in symptom severity and relapse patterns so that resource allocation and policy decisions can be adjusted accordingly, without compromising the welfare of students.\n",
    "\n",
    "------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "### **Datasets That We Have Considered In Our Project:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **IHME Global Burden Of Disease Depressive-Disorders Dataset**\n",
    "\n",
    "    This dataset provides nationally representative estimates of depression prevalence in Singapore. It disaggregates data by age group and sex, including both percentage rates and absolute case counts, offering a detailed view of how depressive disorders affect different segments of the population. Of particular relevance is the extraction of data for the 15 to 24 age range, which allows for focused analysis on university-aged youths. This granularity makes the dataset valuable for understanding the scale and distribution of depression among young adults in Singapore, supporting targeted interventions and research into mental health challenges faced by this demographic.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Reddit & Twitter Depression Severity Levels Dataset**\n",
    "\n",
    "    This dataset is a collection of raw text posts from Reddit and Twitter that have been labeled according to different levels of depression severity - mild, medium and severe. It is particularly useful for analyzing how individuals express depressive symptoms through language, enabling researchers to identify patterns in word choice, sentiment and emotional tone. By leveraging these labels, we can train models to detect varying degrees of depression in text which helps in distinguishing severe cases that may require urgent support and counseling. Ultimately, this dataset provides a foundation for building tools that can monitor online discourse, flag high-risk individuals and guide timely mental health interventions.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **CBT Dataset**\n",
    "\n",
    "    This dataset captures information about patients undergoing cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT), focusing on their experiences with anxiety and depression. It includes details such as consultation waiting times, the number of counseling sessions attended, the frequency of those sessions, and Patient Health Questionnaire (PHQ) scores recorded across different points in their counseling journey. By analyzing these variables together, the dataset enables exploration of how counseling frequency, session counts, and PHQ score trends interact to influence treatment outcomes. In particular, it provides a foundation for evaluating whether adjustments in session frequency or duration could improve the effectiveness of therapy for students experiencing depression and anxiety, such as those at NUS.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
